<HEADLINE>
<P>
METAL GRANDMOTHER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About Chuck Philips' Aug. 7 article, " 'My Heart Aches,' Mothers in Judas 
Priest Trial Tell of Their Five-Year Ordeal": How chilling that these women 
blame music for their own failure to "do it" (go to therapy themselves). 
</P>
<P>
I worked for five years with disturbed teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
Some of the Christians with whom I worked were so upset by this music that as 
an open-minded, 60-year-old grandma, I got earphones to try to form my own 
opinion. Some of the lyrics were quite philosophical and poetic. The music to 
me offered a release -- a joyous celebration and outlet. I began to go to 
concerts. 
</P>
<P>
This music offers an outlet for kids filled with hypocritical dogma from 
parents who are cruel, narrow and ignorant. 
</P>
<P>
We had 70 kids where I worked. Their parents never tried to change themselves; 
instead they blamed anything that they could to get off the hook themselves. 
</P>
<P>
R. CRAFTS 
</P>
<P>
Venice 
</P>
</TEXT>
