<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: REAL ESTATE: NEW LUXURY HOTELS PROJECTED TO BOOST ECONOMY $5 BILLION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Michael Flagg Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Several new resort hotels planned for the coast could bring an extra $5 billion 
or so to the county's economy. 
</P>
<P>
Accountant Kenneth Leventhal &amp; Co. said 4,700 new resort hotel rooms are on 
the drawing boards in the county, a number that he said is likely to double by 
the end of the decade. 
</P>
<P>
There are 1,700 rooms in local resort hotels now. 
</P>
<P>
All those new rooms should boost the number of tourists who visit the county, 
said Gary Wescombe, one of the accounting firm's partners. In 1988 -- the 
latest figures available -- nearly 35 million tourists visited the county, and 
another million came on business or for conventions. 
</P>
<P>
Those people spent $6.5 billion, tourism officials estimate, nearly a third of 
which was spent on lodging. 
</P>
<P>
The hotels already planned include three in Huntington Beach. (Another just 
recently opened.) They have a total of 1,450 rooms. Then there are three hotels 
-- 2,150 rooms among them -- planned for the coastal hills between Newport 
Beach and Laguna Beach. 
</P>
<P>
And two hotels were planned in Dana Point with a total of about 1,100 rooms, 
but their future has been uncertain, because their Australian developer went 
into receivership last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
